<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>12 Indian Queens Who Challenged Norms</title>
    <link href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/tailwindcss@2.2.19/dist/tailwind.min.css" rel="stylesheet">
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f9;
        }
        .queen-card {
            transition: transform 0.3s ease, box-shadow 0.3s ease;
        }
        .queen-card:hover {
            transform: translateY(-10px);
            box-shadow: 0 10px 20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
        }
        .queen-card h4 {
            color: #85241d;
        }
        .queen-image {
            width: 100%;
            height: 200px;
            object-fit: cover;
            border-radius: 8px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body class="bg-gray-100">
    <!-- Hero Section -->
    <section id="home" class="bg-white-900 py-20 text-center">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-bold text-red-800 mb-6">Indian Queens Who Challenged Norms</h2>
            <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-black-700 max-w-4xl mx-auto mb-8">
                Indian queens broke barriers, defied oppressive systems, and led with unparalleled courage. From resisting colonial powers to challenging patriarchal norms, their legacies continue to inspire. Dive into their stories of valor, sacrifice, and leadership that shaped India’s history and continue to resonate today.
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Queens Section -->
    <section id="queens" class="py-16">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h3 class="text-4xl font-bold text-center text-red-900 mb-12">The Queens of Valor</h3>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
                <!-- Queen 1: Rani Lakshmibai -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Lakshmibai" alt="Rani Lakshmibai" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Lakshmibai of Jhansi</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1828–1858<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Jhansi<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Patriarchy, British Colonial Rule<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Born Manikarnika Tambe in Varanasi, Rani Lakshmibai was educated in martial arts, horse riding, and archery, defying the traditional roles assigned to women. Married to Raja Gangadhar Rao of Jhansi, she became regent after his death.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> During the 1857 Indian Rebellion, she resisted the British Doctrine of Lapse, which denied her adopted son’s right to the throne. Leading an army of men and women, she defended Jhansi Fort in 1858, wielding swords in both hands. Her strategic retreat to Kalpi and final stand at Gwalior, where she died fighting, made her a national icon. Her cry, “Main apni Jhansi nahi doongi” (I will not give my Jhansi), remains legendary.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Rani Lakshmibai’s courage inspired India’s freedom struggle, and she is celebrated in folklore, poetry, and statues across the country.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 2: Rani Chennamma -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Chennamma" alt="Rani Chennamma" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Chennamma of Kittur</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1778–1829<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Kittur<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Colonial Oppression, Gender Roles<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Born in Karnataka, Chennamma married Raja Mallasarja of Kittur and became regent after his death. She was trained in warfare and governance, rare for women of her time.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> In 1824, when the British refused to recognize her adopted son as heir, she led an armed rebellion. Her forces, including women warriors, defeated the British in the first battle, killing Collector John Thackeray. Though captured after a second siege, her resistance inspired later revolts. She also promoted education and local governance.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Rani Chennamma’s statue stands in the Indian Parliament, and her story is taught as an early example of anti-colonial resistance.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 3: Rani Durgavati -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Durgavati" alt="Rani Durgavati" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Durgavati of Gondwana</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1524–1564<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Gondwana<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Male-Dominated Warfare<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Born into the Chandel Rajput family, Durgavati married Dalpat Shah of Gondwana. After his death, she ruled as regent for her young son, Vir Narayan.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> Durgavati expanded Gondwana’s territory, built infrastructure like reservoirs, and maintained a strong army. In 1564, she faced Mughal forces under Asaf Khan. Despite being outnumbered, she led her troops on elephant-back, winning initial battles. Injured by arrows, she chose to die by her own dagger rather than surrender, embodying Rajput honor.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Her capital, Garha-Katanga, and memorials like Rani Durgavati University in Jabalpur honor her contributions to Gondwana’s prosperity and resistance.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 4: Chand Bibi -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Chand+Bibi" alt="Chand Bibi" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Chand Bibi of Ahmednagar</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1550–1599<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Ahmednagar<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Religious and Gender Barriers<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Born into the Deccan Sultanates, Chand Bibi was married to Ali Adil Shah of Bijapur and later became regent of Ahmednagar.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> During the Mughal siege of Ahmednagar in 1595, she led the defense, negotiating a peace treaty to preserve her kingdom. In 1599, facing another Mughal attack, she donned armor and rallied her troops, delaying conquest despite internal betrayals. Her diplomatic skills and bravery bridged Hindu-Muslim divides.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Chand Bibi’s leadership is celebrated in Deccan history, and her story reflects the strength of women in medieval India.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 5: Ahilyabai Holkar -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Ahilyabai+Holkar" alt="Ahilyabai Holkar" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Ahilyabai Holkar of Malwa</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1725–1795<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Malwa<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Widowhood Restrictions, Governance Norms<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Born in a shepherd family, Ahilyabai was chosen by Malhar Rao Holkar for her intelligence. After her husband’s death, she defied widowhood norms to rule Malwa.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> Ahilyabai led military campaigns, promoted trade, and built infrastructure like ghats, wells, and temples, including the restoration of Kashi Vishwanath Temple. Her inclusive policies and justice system earned her the title “Philosopher Queen.” She trained her daughter in governance, further challenging gender norms.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Ahilyabai’s contributions are honored with awards and institutions in her name, and her reign is studied as a model of ethical governance.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 6: Rani Velu Nachiyar -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Velu+Nachiyar" alt="Rani Velu Nachiyar" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Velu Nachiyar of Sivaganga</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1730–1796<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Sivaganga<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Colonial Rule, Gender Norms<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Trained in warfare and languages, Velu Nachiyar ruled Sivaganga with her husband until his death at British hands.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> Exiled after her husband’s death, she formed an army with Maratha and Mysore allies, including a women’s unit led by Kuyili. She pioneered guerrilla tactics and executed a human bomb attack to reclaim Sivaganga in 1780. Her eight-year resistance was a precursor to later freedom struggles.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Known as “Veeramangai” (brave woman), her story is celebrated in Tamil Nadu’s history and folk traditions.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 7: Begum Hazrat Mahal -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Begum+Hazrat+Mahal" alt="Begum Hazrat Mahal" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Begum Hazrat Mahal of Awadh</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1820–1879<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Awadh<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Colonial Rule, Religious Divide<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Born Muhammadi Khanum, she became a consort of Nawab Wajid Ali Shah and regent during the 1857 rebellion.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> After Awadh’s annexation, she led the rebellion in Lucknow, uniting Hindus and Muslims. She captured Lucknow, declared her son Birjis Qadr as ruler, and held the city for months. Exiled to Nepal, she continued advocating for independence.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Her leadership is commemorated with a memorial in Lucknow and recognition in India’s freedom struggle.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 8: Rani Rudrama Devi -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Rudrama+Devi" alt="Rani Rudrama Devi" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Rudrama Devi of Kakatiya</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1262–1289<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Kakatiya Dynasty<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Male Succession, Warfare Norms<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Daughter of King Ganapati Deva, Rudrama was raised as a son and trained in warfare to rule the Kakatiya Dynasty.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> She defended her kingdom against invasions by the Yadavas and Cholas, personally leading battles. Her administrative reforms, like land revenue systems, strengthened the dynasty. She promoted women in governance, challenging patriarchal norms.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Rudrama’s reign is documented in inscriptions, and her statue in Telangana celebrates her as a pioneering female ruler.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 9: Rani Padmini -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Padmini" alt="Rani Padmini" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Padmini of Chittor</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 13th–14th Century<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Mewar<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Honor Over Submission<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Wife of Rana Ratan Singh, Padmini’s beauty and courage are chronicled in Malik Muhammad Jayasi’s epic Padmavat.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> When Alauddin Khilji besieged Chittor in 1303, demanding her surrender, Padmini organized the women of the fort. She led them in jauhar, choosing death over dishonor, inspiring Rajput resistance. Her defiance symbolized female agency in medieval India.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Padmini’s story is celebrated in Rajput folklore, literature, and modern adaptations like films.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 10: Rani Abbakka Chowta -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Abbakka+Chowta" alt="Rani Abbakka Chowta" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Abbakka Chowta of Ullal</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1525–1570<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Ullal<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Colonial Rule, Maritime Warfare<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Born into the Chowta dynasty, Abbakka was trained in military strategy and naval warfare.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> She resisted Portuguese colonization for over 40 years, building a navy and leading guerrilla attacks. Her alliances with local rulers and relentless defense of Ullal earned her the title “Abhaya Rani” (Fearless Queen). Betrayed by her ex-husband, she died in battle.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Abbakka is honored with festivals and a naval ship named after her, recognized as India’s first female freedom fighter.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 11: Rani Tarabai -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Tarabai" alt="Rani Tarabai" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Tarabai of Maratha Empire</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1675–1761<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Maratha Empire<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Male Leadership, Mughal Dominance<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Daughter-in-law of Shivaji, Tarabai became regent for her son after her husband Rajaram’s death.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> From 1700–1707, she led the Maratha resistance against Aurangzeb’s Mughal forces, using guerrilla tactics to recapture forts. Her administrative reforms stabilized the empire, and she ruled Kolhapur independently until 1749. Her diplomacy ensured Maratha survival.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Tarabai’s leadership is documented in Maratha chronicles, and her statue in Kolhapur honors her contributions.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Queen 12: Rani Avantibai -->
                <div class="queen-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Rani+Avantibai" alt="Rani Avantibai" class="queen-image mb-4">
                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">Rani Avantibai of Ramgarh</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                        <strong>Era:</strong> 1831–1858<br>
                        <strong>Kingdom:</strong> Ramgarh<br>
                        <strong>Norms Challenged:</strong> Colonial Rule, Gender Roles<br>
                        <strong>Background:</strong> Married to Raja Vikramaditya of Ramgarh, Avantibai became regent after his death, leading her kingdom during the 1857 rebellion.<br>
                        <strong>Achievements:</strong> She raised an army of tribals and locals, using guerrilla tactics to attack British outposts. Her poetry rallied her troops, and her leadership disrupted colonial control in Mandla. Surrounded in 1858, she chose death over capture.<br>
                        <strong>Legacy:</strong> Avantibai’s courage is honored with statues and a postage stamp, and her story inspires tribal communities in Madhya Pradesh.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
